The FAT* conference has begun the necessary conversation on the
normative implications and ethical ramifications of sociotechnical
systems. However, many scholars have pointed to the limitations
in methodologies and scope of analysis (e.g. [8, 11]). In addition to
these critiques, we add in the fact that those who are most affected
by this technology do not have the skills, training, or technical
aptitude to participate in these conversations. With the exception
of the 2018 FAT* tutorial which featured Terrance Wilkerson (who
had been labeled as likely to highly recidivate by COMPAS) and
his partner, there has been silence from those most impacted by
algorithmic unfairness at FAT*. This silence has been deafening,
as FAT* conversations – with a few notable exceptions (e.g. [1, 4])
– have failed to discuss anti-racist politics, prison abolition, and
social justice.
In response to these well-founded critiques, we offer CtrlZ.AI,
zine fair focused on technology and AI. This event will center per-
spectives and methodologies often overlooked by the FAT* commu-
nity. By pairing CtrlZ.AI with FAT*, we hope to bring the academic
research community into conversation with artists, activists, and
diverse communities affected by algorithmic systems.
Zines are self-published, self-distributed, small-circulation mag-
azines. Both the creation and distribution of zines tends to operate
outside the bounds of mainstream commercial settings, providing
an accessible and liberating alternative to those who may be ex-
cluded from or constrained by traditional publishing options. Zine
culture also plays an important community building role through
person-to-person dissemination and an emphasis on knowledge
sharing and personal experiences.
Our CRAFT workshop will bring the FAT* community into con-
versation with artists, activists, and communities affected by these
technologies. We chose to place this engagement within the context
of a zine fair since zine culture embodies an alternative orienta-
tion and mindset. Specifically, zines represent an accessible and
community-oriented mode of creating and disseminating content.
