Cyborg’s "A People’s Guide to AI" [10] connects AI to the ubiquity
of automated decision-making systems in everyday life and relates
AI development to issues of access, power, and speculative futures
(2018).
By centering the way in which diverse communities experience
technologies, we hope to bring fresh and important perspectives
into the FAT* community. In accordance with similar interventions,
such as theDesign Justice andOurData Bodies projects, we envision
an environment in which the knowledge and life experiences from
these communities are centered and taken seriously. As discussed
further below, we will provide a space for DIY creators to circulate
and showcase their work. Zines also play an important role in
subversive social movements and grassroots activism communities
[5–7]. FAT* has been criticized for its tendency to shy away from
justice oriented discourse and work [3]. We hope this zine fair with
provide an opportunity for data and tech justice advocates to come
into conversation with the FAT* community. We also recognize
zines as important knowledge-sharing and community-building
tools [9]. In addition to creating a platform for activists and artists
to showcase their work, we will also facilitate a session whereby
collective learnings and experiences can be distilled into a zine with
low barriers to both creation and readership.
The CtrlZ.AI zine and art fair will run for eight hours at an
external site and consist of four components. First, the fair itself
will be open to a set of contributing tablers who will present and
sell their own work. Second, we will feature a curated selection
of physical zines available from contributors who cannot be co-
present for the fair. Third, we will call for artifacts which may not
be full zines, but can be incorporated or fleshed out in the course of
the event. This can include images, quotes, or parts of zines which
are unfinished prior to the event. Lastly, we will hold three hours
of workshop sessions over the course of the event.
